Set : In Java, a Set is a core part of the Collections Framework used in Data Structures and Algorithms (DSA) to store a collection of unique elements.
It does not allow duplicate entries and does not provide index-based access.

Key Characteristics
No Duplicates: The primary feature of a Set is that it automatically ignores any attempt to add an element that is already present.
No Order Guarantee: In general, Set implementations do not guarantee the order of elements (with the exception of LinkedHashSet and TreeSet).
Efficient Operations: Sets are designed for efficient membership testing (checking if an element exists), insertion, and deletion operations.
Mathematical Operations: They allow for common mathematical set operations like union, intersection, and difference.

Common Implementations in Java
Java provides several classes that implement the Set interface, each with different underlying data structures and performance characteristics: 
HashSet:
Data Structure: Uses a hash table for storage.
Order: Does not maintain any order.
Performance: Offers constant time O(1) on average for basic operations (add, remove, contains), making it very fast.
LinkedHashSet:
Data Structure: Uses a hash table and a doubly linked list.
Order: Maintains the insertion order of elements.
Performance: Slightly slower than HashSet but still efficient.
TreeSet:
Data Structure: Uses a balanced binary search tree (specifically a Red-Black tree).
Order: Stores elements in sorted (ascending) order.
Performance: Operations have a time complexity of O(log n), which is slower than hash-based sets but provides the benefit of ordering. TreeSet does not allow null values.

